ศอออออออออออออออผ

ษออออออออออป
บ Keyboard บ
ศออออออออออผ
Arrow keys:	 Move ship
CTRL: 		 Shoot missiles
ALT:		 Drop bomb

ษออออออออออป
บ Joystick บ
ศออออออออออผ
Joystick: 	 Move ship
Button 1: 	 Shoot missiles
Button 2: 	 Drop bomb


ษอออออออออออออออป
บ Miscellaneous บ
ศอออออออออออออออผ
Space:	 	 Drop nuke
Esc:		 End game
F1:		 Pause game
F2:		 SB Music on/off
F3:		 SB New song
F4:		 SB Effects on/off
+                Increase Game Speed
-                Decrease Game Speed

The alien defense bases will shoot at you using various types of missiles,
which you must avoid.  Some bases are placed so you must destroy them with
a bomb.  You must use some strategy to destroy the bases with the least
amount of damage to your own ship.

To rescue a hostage, first shoot the buildings they are being held in.  They
will start running around, trying to get your attention.  To pick them up,
simply move on to them.  They will get into your ship and be transported
to your home planet.

If you only have one ship left, and your shields are below half, the screen
will begin to flash purple, as a warning that you should be more careful.

If you are using the commercial version of World Quest, press L while
playing the game for extra lives when you're in trouble.  This allows you
to play the whole game without using level codes.


ษอออออออออออออป
บ Level Codes บ
ศอออออออออออออผ
Each level has a level code that you can enter.  If you type in a correct
code, the game will begin at that level.  Level codes are shown on the status
screen after you've finished a level.  Be using level codes, you will be
able to play all of the levels, however your score will start at 0
regardless of where you begin.



ษอออออออออออออออออออป
บ About World Quest บ
ศอออออออออออออออออออผ
World Quest V2.0b was created with the WordUp Graphics Toolkit V4.0.
This toolkit was created to help programmers easily design games or
other graphic intensive programs. It features:

	-320x200x256 color VGA mode (best for games)
	-Graphics primitives
		-points,lines,rectangles,bars,circles, and more
	-4 way scrolling library:
		-VISUALLY design game worlds up to 320x200 tiles
		-Have up to 1000 sprites moving within game world
		   (this game only uses 150 sprites!)
		-Fast scrolling in any direction
	-Sprite library
		-used with static backgrounds
		-up to 40 independantly animating and moving sprites
		-set up movement and animation once with a few commands
		   and sprites continue to move on their own
		-movements and animation can repeat any number of times
	-Drop down menu library
		-Graphical menu system with source code (registered)
	-Input routines
		-Mouse and joystick routines are both included
	-Palette manipulation
		-Load, save and rotate palettes
	-Image transfer
		-FAST transers with copy or 'xray' mode 
	-Special effects
		-resize, warp, wipe, skew, flip and fade images
	-FLI/FLC playing library
		-Play FLI/FLC files from memory (registered)
		-Use sprite library to show sprites overtop of FLI as
		    it is playing!
		-Perform special effects on FLI, eg resize FLI as it plays
	-Custom fonts
		-Edit the included fonts or design your own!
	-Timing controls
		-Slow down fast computers so your game runs at the same
		   speed regardless of the computer it is played on
	-WGT library
		-Combine all graphics data (or ANY data) into one large
		password protected library file. This protects your
		graphics from other users of WGT. 
	-All routines have full clipping
	-Requires Turbo C++ or Borland C++



